interactions.lmstext: 1. The hypodermis is also known as the _________________ fascia.
2. What is fascia?

choices.lmstext: Fascia is a connective tissue layer observable to the naked eye.
Fascia is a general term for connective tissue.
Fascia is another term for “layer”; it can refer to a layer of any tissue type.
Fascia is a connective tissue layer specifically associated with skin.

interactions.lmstext: 3. What are intercostal nerves? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: derived from T1 - T11 spinal nerves

interactions.lmstext: 4. Which intercostal nerves contribute to the innervation of the abdominal wall?
5. Which functional fibre types are present in intercostal nerves? Choose all that apply.
6. What are grey rami communicantes? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: Grey rami communicantes contain sympathetic postganglionic fibres.
Grey rami communicantes innervate the thoracic body wall.
Grey rami communicantes contain unmyelinated axons.
Grey rami communicantes innervate thoracic viscera.
Grey rami communicantes contain sympathetic preganglionic fibres.
Grey rami communicantes contain myelinated axons.

interactions.lmstext: 7. What are white rami communicantes? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: White rami communicantes axons that innervate thoracic viscera.
White rami communicantes contain sympathetic preganglionic fibres.
White rami communicantes contain axons that innervate the thoracic body wall.
White rami communicantes contain myelinated axons.
White rami communicantes contain sympathetic postganglionic fibres.
White rami communicantes contain unmyelinated axons.

interactions.lmstext: 8. Where are the target tissues of the postganglionic cell bodies contained within sympathetic chain ganglia? Choose all that apply.
9. What is a splanchnic nerve? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: a nerve that contains postganglionic fibres
a nerve that contains preganglionic fibres
a nerve that contains sympathetic fibres
a nerve that contains parasympathetic fibres
a nerve that innervates the body wall and limbs

interactions.lmstext: 10. What is a terminal ganglion? Choose all that apply.

choices.lmstext: a ganglion located near its target organ
a collection of parasympathetic postganglionic neuronal cell bodies
a ganglion located within the wall of its target organ
a collection of sympathetic preganglionic neuronal cell bodies
a collection of sympathetic postganglionic neuronal cell bodies
a collection of parasympathetic preganglionic neuronal cell bodies

interactions.lmstext: 11. Which functional fibre types feed into the cardiac plexus?
12. Which of the following contain sensory fibres that carry information regarding normal cardiovascular function toward the central nervous system? Choose all that apply.

13. Which of the following contain sensory fibres that carry information regarding tissue damage (ultimately interpreted as pain) from the esophagus toward the central nervous system? Choose all that apply.
14. Sensory fibres that convey pain from the heart to the CNS travel through which of the following structures? Choose all that apply.
15. What is interstitial fluid? Choose all that apply..

choices.lmstext: It is the medium through which oxygen and nutrients diffuse from blood to cells.
It is the medium through which carbon dioxide and metabolic wastes diffuse from cells to blood.
It is filtered through lymph nodes.

interactions.lmstext: 16. There are no lymphatics in the bone marrow.
17. With which body region are superficial lymph nodes associated?
18. _______ lymph nodes are associated with internal body surfaces, such as the airways and digestive tract.
19. With which body region are the axillary lymph nodes associated?
20. With which body region are the inguinal lymph nodes associated?
21. With which body region are the cervical lymph nodes associated?
22. With which body region are the pericranial lymph nodes associated?
23. From which body region does the bronchomediastinal trunk collect lymph?

choices.lmstext: right side: i) head and neck, ii) arm and axilla, iii) thoracic viscera

interactions.lmstext: 24. From which body region does the internal jugular trunk collect lymph?

choices.lmstext: right side: i) head and neck, ii) arm and axilla, iii) thoracic viscera

interactions.lmstext: 25. From which body region does the subclavian trunk collect lymph?

choices.lmstext: right side: i) head and neck, ii) arm and axilla, iii) thoracic viscera

interactions.lmstext: 26. From which body region does the right lymphatic duct collect lymph?

choices.lmstext: right side: i) head and neck, ii) arm and axilla, iii) thoracic viscera

interactions.lmstext: 27. From which body regions does the thoracic duct collect lymph? Choose all that apply.
